<subSubSection pageId="12" pageNumber="609" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="12.[1966,2559,289,718]" pageId="12" pageNumber="609">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Thomas" authorityYear="1888" box="[1968,2326,289,323]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Lophuromys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="12" pageNumber="609" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="flavopunctatus">Lophuromys flavopunctatus</taxonomicName>
was considered widespread from Ethiopia to East and Central Africa, but various authors restricted its distribution to Ethiopia only. Different morphological, morphometric, cytogenetic, and molecular studies successively rehabilitated 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Thomas" authorityYear="1906" box="[2239,2395,534,559]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Lophuromys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="12" pageNumber="609" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="brunneus">L. brunneus</taxonomicName>
, L. simensis, L. zaphiri, and 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="True" baseAuthorityYear="1892" box="[2169,2300,564,598]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Lophuromys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="12" pageNumber="609" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="aquilus">L. aquilus</taxonomicName>
to distinct species. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Thomas" authorityYear="1888" box="[1968,2322,604,638]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Lophuromys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="12" pageNumber="609" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="flavopunctatus">Lophuromys flavopunctatus</taxonomicName>
is very similar to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Thomas" authorityYear="1906" box="[1969,2133,648,677]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Lophuromys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="12" pageNumber="609" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="brunneus">L. brunneus</taxonomicName>
but have different cytotypes and some genetic distance. Monotypic.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[1355,2374,723,757]" pageId="12" pageNumber="609" type="distribution">
<caption box="[1355,2374,723,757]" inLine="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="609" targetBox="[2328,2332,1288,1309]" targetPageId="12">
<paragraph blockId="12.[1354,2561,723,1309]" box="[1355,2374,723,757]" pageId="12" pageNumber="609">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1355,1531,723,757]" pageId="12" pageNumber="609">Distribution.</emphasis>
Known from several localities W of the Rift Valley, Ethiopia.
</paragraph>
</caption>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="12" pageNumber="609" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="12.[1354,2561,723,1309]" pageId="12" pageNumber="609">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1355,1605,771,796]" pageId="12" pageNumber="609">Descriptive notes.</emphasis>
Head-body 125-129 mm, tail 58-68 mm, ear 17-19 mm, hindfoot 23-25-3 mm; weight 69 g. The Buffspotted Brush-furred Rat is small, with speckled red-brown dorsum; venter is pale red. Tail is relatively short, ¢.50% of head-body length.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[1355,2516,920,954]" pageId="12" pageNumber="609" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="12.[1354,2561,723,1309]" box="[1355,2516,920,954]" pageId="12" pageNumber="609">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1355,1466,920,954]" pageId="12" pageNumber="609">Habitat.</emphasis>
Poorly known but various Ethiopian habitats at elevations of 1900-3000 m
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
